---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Psychiatric 1 — Cecil Whitver"
  description="Unfolding case study: Major Depressive Disorder in an Elderly Hospitalized Patient (PSYCH-01)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/psychiatric/`}>Psychiatric</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Psychiatric 1 — Cecil Whitver</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Mental Health / Depression</span>
    <h1>Psychiatric 1 — Cecil Whitver</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Major Depressive Disorder in an Elderly Hospitalized Patient</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Cecil Whitver, 78 years, Male</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20–25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20–25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- PHASE 1 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You are the nurse assigned to Cecil Whitver on the medical-surgical unit. He was admitted for dehydration. You review the handoff report and medication administration record before entering his room.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Cecil Whitver</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / Gender</th><td>78 years · Male</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Dehydration</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Secondary Dx</th><td>Major depressive disorder (known history)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Medical History</th><td>Depression, malnutrition, limited social support</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Admission</th><td>From home via emergency department</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Medications on MAR</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li>IV fluids: 0.9% Normal Saline at 100 mL/hr</li>
          <li>Sertraline (Zoloft) 50 mg PO daily</li>
          <li>Nutritional supplements PO</li>
          <li>Acetaminophen PO PRN</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>Cecil is lying in bed, staring at the ceiling. He gives a minimal response when you enter. His affect is flat; his voice is quiet and monotone. The room is dim, and he has not touched his breakfast tray.</p>
      <p>"What's the point?" he says quietly, not making eye contact.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What is the connection between depression and dehydration in elderly patients?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Depression in elderly patients creates a cascade that directly leads to physical illness:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Anorexia and anergia</strong> from depression reduce motivation to eat or drink — Cecil is not touching his tray.</li>
          <li><strong>Decreased thirst sensation</strong> is normal in aging; combined with depression, oral intake drops dramatically.</li>
          <li><strong>Polypharmacy side effects</strong> (including some antidepressants) can cause dry mouth or GI symptoms, further reducing intake.</li>
          <li><strong>Cognitive changes and hopelessness</strong> ("what's the point?") eliminate the motivation to self-care.</li>
          <li><strong>Clinical implication:</strong> Cecil's admission reason (dehydration) is a <em>direct consequence</em> of undertreated depression, not an unrelated medical problem. Treating the dehydration without addressing the depression will result in readmission.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You begin your psychosocial assessment…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 2 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Recognizing Depression in Elderly Patients</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You begin your psychosocial assessment. Cecil answers in monosyllables. You recognize signs that extend well beyond the admitting diagnosis of dehydration.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 DSM-5 Criteria — Major Depressive Disorder</h3>
        <p>Must have <strong>≥ 5 of 9 symptoms</strong> for <strong>2+ weeks</strong>, including either depressed mood or anhedonia:</p>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>SIG E CAPS</th><th>Symptom</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>S</strong></td><td>Sleep disturbance (insomnia or hypersomnia)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>I</strong></td><td>Interest loss (anhedonia) — loss of pleasure in activities</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>G</strong></td><td>Guilt or feelings of worthlessness</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>E</strong></td><td>Energy decrease (fatigue, anergia)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>C</strong></td><td>Concentration impaired</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>A</strong></td><td>Appetite change (decrease or increase)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>P</strong></td><td>Psychomotor changes (slowing or agitation)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>S</strong></td><td>Suicidal ideation or recurrent thoughts of death</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>⚠️ Atypical Presentation in Elderly</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Typical Presentation</th><th>Elderly Presentation</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Sadness</td><td>Somatic complaints (fatigue, pain)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Crying</td><td>Flat affect or denial of sadness</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Verbalizing sadness</td><td>Anorexia and weight loss</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Memory complaints</td><td>Pseudodementia (mimics true cognitive decline)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Hopelessness</td><td>"I'm fine" — dismissal and minimization</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🔍 What You Observe in Cecil</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Flat affect; poor eye contact throughout interaction</li>
        <li>Minimal verbal responses — mostly one-word answers</li>
        <li>Breakfast tray untouched; family reports weeks of poor oral intake</li>
        <li>Appears unkempt; poor hygiene noted</li>
        <li>Slow movements; psychomotor retardation</li>
        <li>States: "I'm tired all the time" and "I just don't care anymore"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Why is depression underdiagnosed in elderly hospitalized patients?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>Symptoms overlap with physical illness — fatigue, poor appetite, and cognitive changes are attributed to the medical problem, not depression.</li>
          <li>Elderly patients may deny feeling depressed but will acknowledge anhedonia ("I don't enjoy anything anymore") — ask differently.</li>
          <li>Nurses on medical-surgical units may attribute withdrawal and flat affect to "normal aging" — it is not normal.</li>
          <li>Limited psychiatric training on general nursing units creates knowledge gaps.</li>
          <li>Time constraints prevent psychosocial assessment depth during busy shifts.</li>
          <li>Atypical presentation (somatic focus, no tears, no overt sadness) misleads assessors.</li>
          <li><strong>Result:</strong> Depression in elderly hospitalized patients has a detection rate estimated as low as 25–30% without structured screening tools (e.g., GDS — Geriatric Depression Scale).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You sit down with Cecil to build therapeutic rapport…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 3 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Therapeutic Communication with a Depressed Patient</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You sit down with Cecil — unhurried, at eye level. You use therapeutic communication techniques to build trust and gather more comprehensive information about his experience.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>✅ Therapeutic Communication Techniques</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Technique</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Open-ended questions</td><td>"How have you been feeling lately?"</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Active listening</td><td>Nodding, reflecting feelings back to patient</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Validation</td><td>"It sounds like things have been really difficult for you."</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Therapeutic silence</td><td>Allowing pauses without filling them; conveying presence</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Normalizing</td><td>"Many people who have been through what you have feel this way."</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>❌ What NOT to Say</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Platitude</th><th>Why It's Harmful</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>"Cheer up!"</td><td>Dismisses the patient's reality; implies it's a choice</td></tr>
            <tr><td>"Things could be worse."</td><td>Invalidating — minimizes their suffering</td></tr>
            <tr><td>"You have so much to live for."</td><td>False reassurance; creates pressure and shame</td></tr>
            <tr><td>"Everyone feels that way."</td><td>Minimizing — undermines the severity of their experience</td></tr>
            <tr><td>"Just think positively."</td><td>Implies depression is a mindset they can simply change</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>💬 Therapeutic Dialogue Example</h3>
      <p><strong>Nurse:</strong> "Cecil, you mentioned you haven't been eating much. Can you tell me more about that?"</p>
      <p><strong>Cecil:</strong> "I just don't see the point anymore."</p>
      <p><strong>Nurse:</strong> "It sounds like things have been feeling really hopeless for you. How long have you been feeling this way?"</p>
      <p><em>[The nurse validates the feeling, uses open-ended language, and invites deeper exploration without judgment or dismissal.]</em></p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why is sitting down with a depressed patient therapeutically significant?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Posture communicates presence.</strong> Sitting down signals to the patient that you are not in a hurry — a powerful non-verbal message.</li>
          <li><strong>Eye level removes power differential.</strong> Standing over a patient in bed conveys authority and distance; sitting conveys equality and engagement.</li>
          <li><strong>Non-verbal communication is as important as words.</strong> Depressed patients are highly sensitive to perceived rejection and dismissal.</li>
          <li><strong>Depressed patients often interpret hurried behavior</strong> as confirmation that they are a burden — reinforcing hopelessness.</li>
          <li><strong>Research shows</strong> that nurses who sit during patient interactions are perceived as spending more time even when actual time is equal to standing interactions.</li>
          <li>Sitting for even 5 minutes with full attention dramatically increases the patient's sense of being heard and valued.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Cecil makes a statement that requires immediate clinical attention…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 4 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Suicide Risk Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Cecil says: "I'm tired of everything. Sometimes I wonder why I bother." You recognize this as a potential expression of suicidal ideation and prepare to conduct a formal safety assessment.</p>
    <div class="callout callout-danger">
      <strong>🚨 Asking About Suicide Does NOT Plant the Idea — It Is Safe, Necessary, and Standard of Care</strong>
      <p>This is one of the most persistent myths in psychiatric nursing. Research consistently demonstrates that directly asking about suicidal ideation does <em>not</em> increase risk — it decreases risk by opening communication. Every patient expressing hopelessness must be directly assessed.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>⚠️ Suicide Risk Factors — Cecil Whitver</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Risk Factor</th><th>Relevance</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Male gender</td><td>Men complete suicide at rates 3–4× higher than women</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Age ≥ 75 years</td><td>Highest risk demographic — older White males in particular</td></tr>
            <tr><td>History of depression</td><td>Strongest predictor of suicidal ideation</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Social isolation</td><td>Limited social support noted in medical history</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Chronic illness</td><td>Dehydration, malnutrition — perception of declining health</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Recent functional decline</td><td>Unable to care for self; hospital admission</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Access to means</td><td>Assess firearms — elderly men have highest firearm suicide rates</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🛡️ Protective Factors to Assess</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Protective Factor</th><th>Purpose of Assessment</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Religious / spiritual beliefs</td><td>May serve as a reason for living</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Social connections and family</td><td>Relationships that provide meaning</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Reasons for living</td><td>Explicit identification strengthens safety</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Engagement in treatment</td><td>Willingness to seek help is protective</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Future orientation</td><td>Ability to imagine a future reduces acute risk</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🔑 Directly Asking the Safety Question</h3>
      <p>"Cecil, I want to ask you something important. Sometimes when people feel very low — tired of everything — they have thoughts about not wanting to be here anymore. Have you been having thoughts like that?"</p>
      <p><strong>If the patient says YES:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Stay with the patient — do not leave them alone</li>
        <li>Notify the provider and charge nurse immediately</li>
        <li>Initiate safety precautions per unit protocol</li>
        <li>Remove any accessible means from the environment</li>
        <li>Document all statements verbatim (use quotation marks)</li>
        <li>Initiate psychiatric consultation</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Reporting Suicidal Ideation to the Provider</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>I'm calling about Cecil Whitver, a 78-year-old male admitted for dehydration. During my assessment he expressed hopelessness and possible suicidal ideation, stating "I'm tired of everything. Sometimes I wonder why I bother."</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>Cecil has a history of major depressive disorder. He has been eating and drinking very little for weeks — his dehydration is likely a consequence of depression-related anorexia. He is currently on sertraline 50 mg PO daily. He is 78 years old, male, with limited social support — all significant risk factors for suicide completion.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>I directly asked the safety question. Cecil [did / did not] express active suicidal ideation. His affect is flat, he is withdrawn, and he states "I don't see the point anymore." I assess him as high risk given his demographic profile and expressed hopelessness.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting: psychiatric consultation today; order for 1:1 monitoring; safety precautions initiated; review of sertraline dosing; social work referral for discharge planning and support assessment.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ The interdisciplinary team responds and you coordinate Cecil's care plan…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 5 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Collaborative Care and Safety Planning</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You have notified the provider and initiated a psychiatric referral. The interdisciplinary team responds to develop a comprehensive plan addressing both Cecil's physical and mental health needs.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Interdisciplinary Interventions</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>Psychiatric / mental health consultation</strong> — psychiatrist or LCSW evaluation</li>
          <li><strong>Antidepressant review</strong> — is sertraline at therapeutic dose? Consider dose adjustment</li>
          <li><strong>Social work referral</strong> — assess home situation, supports, discharge planning</li>
          <li><strong>Nutritional assessment</strong> — dietitian consult for depression-related malnutrition</li>
          <li><strong>Cognitive screening</strong> — MMSE or MoCA to rule out dementia vs. pseudodementia</li>
          <li><strong>Fall risk assessment</strong> — depression plus medications increases fall risk significantly</li>
          <li><strong>Activity / engagement</strong> — encourage gradual self-care participation</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🏠 Discharge Safety Considerations</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Safety Concern</th><th>Action Required</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Lives alone</td><td>Social work evaluation for home support</td></tr>
            <tr><td>No visitors noted</td><td>Contact family / caregiver; assess support network</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Firearms at home</td><td>Assess and counsel on safe storage or removal</td></tr>
            <tr><td>No follow-up arranged</td><td>Connect to outpatient mental health services before discharge</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Refuses treatment</td><td>Capacity evaluation; explore barriers to engagement</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>💊 Sertraline (Zoloft) — SSRI in Elderly Patients</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Class:</strong> Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) — first-line treatment for MDD in elderly</li>
        <li><strong>Therapeutic onset:</strong> 4–6 weeks — patient education is critical to prevent premature discontinuation</li>
        <li><strong>Common side effects:</strong> Nausea, insomnia, sexual dysfunction, headache</li>
        <li><strong>Monitor for serotonin syndrome</strong> (rare but serious): agitation, diaphoresis, clonus, hyperthermia, tachycardia</li>
        <li><strong>Fall risk:</strong> Orthostatic hypotension and dizziness — assess BP changes with position changes</li>
        <li><strong>NEVER abruptly discontinue</strong> — taper required to avoid discontinuation syndrome</li>
        <li><strong>Suicide monitoring:</strong> Paradoxically, early weeks of SSRI therapy require close monitoring for increased ideation as energy improves before mood lifts</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why do antidepressants take 4–6 weeks to work?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>This is one of the most important patient education points — and one of the most misunderstood aspects of antidepressant therapy.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Common misconception:</strong> SSRIs simply "increase serotonin" and should work immediately.</li>
          <li><strong>Reality — Neuroplasticity Hypothesis:</strong> The acute serotonin increase happens within hours, but this is NOT the mechanism of therapeutic effect.</li>
          <li>The therapeutic benefit comes from <strong>downstream neuroplasticity changes</strong>:
            <ul>
              <li>Increased <strong>BDNF</strong> (Brain-Derived Neurotrophic Factor) — promotes new neuron growth</li>
              <li>Changes in <strong>receptor density</strong> and receptor sensitivity</li>
              <li><strong>Neurogenesis in the hippocampus</strong> — the hippocampus is atrophied in depression; SSRIs help reverse this</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>These neuroplastic adaptations take <strong>3–6 weeks</strong> to develop — explaining the delayed therapeutic window.</li>
          <li><strong>Clinical implication:</strong> Premature discontinuation (within the first 2–3 weeks because "it's not working") is the most common cause of treatment failure. Cecil needs this explained clearly.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You complete your assessment and prepare comprehensive documentation…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 6 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase6">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 6</span>
      <h2>Nursing Diagnoses and SBAR</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You complete your assessment and prioritize Cecil's nursing care. Documentation is precise and the interdisciplinary team is fully engaged in his plan of care.</p>
    <h3>📋 Priority Nursing Diagnoses</h3>
    <div class="dx-rank-list">
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">1</span>
        <div><strong>Hopelessness r/t chronic depression and perceived loss of meaningful life</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: verbal expression "I don't see the point anymore," flat affect, minimal participation in care, expressed anhedonia</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">2</span>
        <div><strong>Deficient Fluid Volume r/t inadequate oral intake secondary to depression and anorexia</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: dehydration requiring IV fluid replacement; history of weeks of poor oral intake</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">3</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Suicide r/t depression, advanced age, male gender, and social isolation</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: multiple risk factors present; expressed hopelessness; statement "I'm tired of everything"</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">4</span>
        <div><strong>Imbalanced Nutrition: Less Than Body Requirements r/t anorexia and anergia from depression</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: untouched breakfast tray; family reports weeks of poor oral intake; malnutrition noted in medical history</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">5</span>
        <div><strong>Social Isolation r/t depression and limited social support</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: elderly male, minimal visitors, withdrawn communication, limited social support in history</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Calling the Provider About Cecil's Depression and Dehydration</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>I'm calling about Cecil Whitver, a 78-year-old male admitted for dehydration. My assessment reveals significant depression and safety concerns requiring immediate attention.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>Cecil has a known history of major depressive disorder. He has had weeks of poor oral intake that directly caused his current dehydration. He is currently on sertraline 50 mg PO daily. He is flat affect, anhedonic, and stated "I'm tired of everything." He is 78 years old, male, with limited social support — multiple suicide risk factors present.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>Direct suicide safety assessment performed — patient [expressed / denied] active suicidal ideation. His dehydration is a direct consequence of depression-related anorexia. He requires psychiatric evaluation today. Safety precautions have been initiated.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting: psychiatric consultation today; confirm sertraline dose — consider adjustment; social work referral for home safety and discharge planning; order 1:1 safety precautions if ideation is active; dietitian consult for malnutrition; cognitive screening order.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX A -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Appendix: Reference Materials</div>
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-a">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medications</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table med-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Medication</th>
          <th>Class</th>
          <th>Key Nursing Points</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Sertraline (Zoloft) 50 mg PO daily</strong></td>
          <td>SSRI antidepressant</td>
          <td>First-line for MDD in elderly; therapeutic onset 4–6 weeks; monitor for serotonin syndrome (agitation, diaphoresis, clonus, hyperthermia); fall risk (dizziness, orthostatic hypotension); NEVER abruptly discontinue; assess suicidal ideation — especially in first weeks of therapy when energy returns before mood lifts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>0.9% Normal Saline IV 100 mL/hr</strong></td>
          <td>Isotonic crystalloid</td>
          <td>Treatment of dehydration; monitor fluid balance (I&amp;O); watch for signs of fluid overload (edema, crackles, shortness of breath); assess IV site hourly for infiltration or phlebitis</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Nutritional supplements PO</strong></td>
          <td>Supportive nutrition</td>
          <td>Addresses malnutrition from depression-related anorexia; involve dietitian in care plan; document oral intake percentages at each meal; encourage patient participation in food choices</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX B -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Discussion Questions</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: What is the most appropriate nursing response when a patient expresses hopelessness?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>The most appropriate response is to use <strong>therapeutic communication</strong>: acknowledge and validate the feeling, remain present (sit down, make eye contact), and use open-ended questions to explore the depth of hopelessness. Most importantly, directly assess for suicidal ideation — "Sometimes when people feel this hopeless, they have thoughts about not wanting to be here. Have you been having thoughts like that?" Do not minimize, offer platitudes, or change the subject. Document the patient's exact words in quotation marks.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: Why might depression be missed in elderly hospitalized patients?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Depression is underdiagnosed in elderly hospitalized patients because: (1) symptoms overlap with physical illness; (2) elderly patients may not report sadness but will acknowledge anhedonia if asked directly; (3) medical-surgical nurses may lack psychiatric assessment training; (4) flat affect and withdrawal may be attributed to "normal aging"; (5) atypical somatic presentation (fatigue, pain) draws attention away from mental health; (6) time constraints prevent thorough psychosocial assessment. Structured screening tools like the <strong>Geriatric Depression Scale (GDS)</strong> improve detection rates significantly.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: What are the components of SIG E CAPS?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>SIG E CAPS</strong> is a mnemonic for the DSM-5 criteria for major depressive disorder:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>S</strong> — Sleep disturbance (insomnia or hypersomnia)</li>
          <li><strong>I</strong> — Interest loss (anhedonia)</li>
          <li><strong>G</strong> — Guilt or feelings of worthlessness</li>
          <li><strong>E</strong> — Energy decrease (fatigue, anergia)</li>
          <li><strong>C</strong> — Concentration impaired</li>
          <li><strong>A</strong> — Appetite change</li>
          <li><strong>P</strong> — Psychomotor changes (retardation or agitation)</li>
          <li><strong>S</strong> — Suicidal ideation or recurrent thoughts of death</li>
        </ul>
        <p>≥ 5 symptoms for 2+ weeks, including either depressed mood or anhedonia = diagnosis of MDD.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: What is the nurse's immediate priority when a patient expresses suicidal ideation?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Immediate priorities in order: (1) <strong>Stay with the patient — do not leave them alone</strong>; (2) Notify the provider and charge nurse immediately; (3) Initiate safety precautions per unit protocol (remove sharps, call bell within reach, bed in low position); (4) Remove any accessible means from environment; (5) Initiate psychiatric consultation; (6) Document all statements verbatim in quotation marks; (7) Communicate plan to all team members. The safety of the patient is the absolute first priority — all other nursing tasks are secondary until safety is established.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What is the pathophysiology linking depression to dehydration in this patient?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>Depression causes <strong>anorexia and anergia</strong> (lack of energy and motivation) which dramatically reduce oral intake of food and fluids. Combined with the <strong>normal age-related decrease in thirst sensation</strong> in elderly patients, Cecil loses the drive to eat or drink even when physiologically dehydrated. The hopelessness component ("what's the point?") further eliminates motivation for self-care. Over weeks, this progressive reduction in oral intake results in clinically significant dehydration requiring IV fluid resuscitation. Treating the dehydration alone without addressing the underlying depression will result in a cycle of readmissions.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

